{
  "text": "Assays for \u03b2-galactosidase were performed as described previously [CITATION_1] . Briefly, multiple colonies were scraped off each plate and transferred to 1 ml of distilled water. After thorough mixing, D '!! measurements of each suspension were taken so that \u03b2-galactosidase activities could be normalized to the density of yeast cells. Equivalent units of yeast were transferred to microfuge tubes and pelleted by brief centrifugation. The supernatant was removed and the cells were resuspended in 500 \u00b5l of Z buffer (100 mM NaPO % , pH 7.0, 10 mM KCl, 1 mM MgSO % and 38 mM \u03b2-mercaptoethanol). A 50 \u00b5l aliquot of 0.1 % SDS was added and the cells were vortexed vigorously for 15 s. Chloroform (50 \u00b5l) was then added and the cells were vortexed for an additional 15 s. Assays for \u03b2-galactosidase were immediately initiated by the addition of 100 \u00b5l of 4 mg\\ml o-nitrophenyl \u03b2-\uf764-galactopyranoside and incubations were conducted at 37 mC. Reactions were terminated by the addition of 500 \u00b5l of 1 M Na # CO $ . Reaction mixtures were centrifuged for 1 min and the A %#! was measured. \u03b2-Galactosidase activities in Miller units were calculated according to the formula as follows :",
  "correct_citation": {
